WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.337 --> 00:00:07.440
[Michael]
Where is everyone?

00:00:07.473 --> 00:00:10.643
We have been listening
for messages from outer space

00:00:10.676 --> 00:00:13.579
for more than half a century,

00:00:13.612 --> 00:00:15.482
and so far...

00:00:17.516 --> 00:00:19.552
silence.

00:00:19.585 --> 00:00:21.087
Why?

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.158
Are we truly alone
in the universe?

00:00:25.191 --> 00:00:28.194
Or is everyone else
acting like us

00:00:28.227 --> 00:00:31.097
and just doing a lot
of listening?

00:00:31.130 --> 00:00:33.199
Maybe we need to be louder.

00:00:33.232 --> 00:00:36.736
Maybe we need to send
more messages out there.

00:00:36.769 --> 00:00:39.672
But how do you write a letter
to an extraterrestrial

00:00:39.705 --> 00:00:42.742
whose language and culture
and biology and mind

00:00:42.775 --> 00:00:44.811
we have no concept of?

00:00:44.844 --> 00:00:46.512
And what do you say?

00:00:46.545 --> 00:00:50.750
And given all of the unknowns
about what they might be,

00:00:50.783 --> 00:00:53.686
should we say
anything at all?

00:00:53.719 --> 00:00:58.491
<i> ♪♪</i>

00:01:14.206 --> 00:01:15.641
Ever since I was a kid,

00:01:15.674 --> 00:01:18.244
I've wanted to design
a message

00:01:18.277 --> 00:01:20.379
that is sent
to outer space.

00:01:20.412 --> 00:01:23.516
A sort of hello from Earth
to whatever extraterrestrials

00:01:23.549 --> 00:01:25.251
might be out there.

00:01:25.284 --> 00:01:28.654
I mean, come on, to be
the author of the first thing

00:01:28.687 --> 00:01:31.290
aliens ever heard
from our entire planet

00:01:31.323 --> 00:01:33.626
would be a fantastic honor.

00:01:33.659 --> 00:01:34.861
And as it turns out,

00:01:34.894 --> 00:01:37.697
an opportunity to send
a message to space

00:01:37.730 --> 00:01:40.533
has been given to me.

00:01:40.566 --> 00:01:43.169
But it might
be a waste of time.

00:01:43.202 --> 00:01:48.875
What if there isn't anything or
anyone out there to receive it?

00:01:48.908 --> 00:01:51.144
The fact that we still have
no evidence

00:01:51.177 --> 00:01:52.245
of intelligent alien life

00:01:52.278 --> 00:01:56.282
despite the high probability
that such life exists,

00:01:56.315 --> 00:01:58.184
is called the Fermi paradox.

00:01:58.217 --> 00:01:59.752
And there are many
entertaining theories

00:01:59.785 --> 00:02:01.721
that attempt to explain it.

00:02:01.754 --> 00:02:03.623
One explanation
is the theory

00:02:03.656 --> 00:02:06.359
that whenever two
civilizations meet,

00:02:06.392 --> 00:02:09.295
destruction always results.

00:02:09.328 --> 00:02:11.564
Which is why in 2015,

00:02:11.597 --> 00:02:13.766
several prominent experts
wrote a letter

00:02:13.799 --> 00:02:17.803 line:0%
warning against making
any contact at all.

00:02:17.836 --> 00:02:21.307 line:0%
[Stephen Hawking]

00:02:36.222 --> 00:02:39.559
Ideas like that suggest that
perhaps we should remain silent,

00:02:39.592 --> 00:02:42.195
send no messages to space.

00:02:42.228 --> 00:02:44.597
But Doug Vakoch
disagrees.

00:02:44.630 --> 00:02:46.866
He is the president of METI,

00:02:46.899 --> 00:02:50.336
an organization that,
despite all of these concerns,

00:02:50.369 --> 00:02:52.738
is nonetheless
actively messaging

00:02:52.771 --> 00:02:55.474
extraterrestrial
intelligence.

00:02:55.507 --> 00:02:57.743
If I want to design a message
for life out there,

00:02:57.776 --> 00:02:59.679
I should talk to him first.

00:02:59.712 --> 00:03:02.849
Why isn't he afraid?

00:03:04.617 --> 00:03:05.651 line:0%
<i> I met up with Doug</i>

00:03:05.684 --> 00:03:07.420 line:0%
<i> at the Chabot Observatory,</i>

00:03:07.453 --> 00:03:10.456 line:0%
<i> home to the largest
 public refractor telescope</i>

00:03:10.489 --> 00:03:12.725
<i> in the Western United States.</i>

00:03:12.758 --> 00:03:14.393
-[Douglas] So here we are.
-[Michael] Wow.

00:03:14.426 --> 00:03:15.561 line:0%
[Douglas]
Yeah.

00:03:15.594 --> 00:03:19.432 line:0%
This was one of the prime
telescopes of a century ago.

00:03:19.465 --> 00:03:22.368
This is really an antique.

00:03:22.401 --> 00:03:25.404
[Michael] Jeez!
I've seen so many observatories

00:03:25.437 --> 00:03:27.673
and so many big telescopes
in pictures.

00:03:27.706 --> 00:03:29.575
Believe it or not, I've never
been this close to one.

00:03:29.608 --> 00:03:31.877
[Douglas]
This is a huge instrument,

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:34.914
and yet it's balanced
too exquisitely.

00:03:34.947 --> 00:03:37.283
I'm like a super person.
Oh!

00:03:37.316 --> 00:03:38.451 align:start position:0%
[Douglas laughs]

00:03:38.484 --> 00:03:40.453
It had quite a bit
of momentum there.

00:03:40.486 --> 00:03:41.654
I'm scared to look.

00:03:41.687 --> 00:03:44.423
I'm telling you, I had no idea
I would have this feeling,

00:03:44.456 --> 00:03:46.525
-seeing a telescope this big.
-[Douglas] Well, it is, it is.

00:03:46.558 --> 00:03:48.594
Can I handle
what I would see?

00:03:48.627 --> 00:03:49.929
I think you can.
I think you can.

00:03:49.962 --> 00:03:51.931 align:start position:0%
You just take a look.

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:54.600
Ah-ha.

00:03:54.633 --> 00:03:56.335
-Absolutely nothing.
-[Douglas] Not tonight.

00:03:56.368 --> 00:03:58.304
-Because of the fog.
-Because of the fog.

00:03:58.337 --> 00:04:01.941
[Michael]
Just the fog coming in
is pretty darn cool.

00:04:03.542 --> 00:04:04.777
<i> The universe has existed</i>

00:04:04.810 --> 00:04:06.178
<i> longer than we have,</i>

00:04:06.212 --> 00:04:09.482
<i> but we've only been actively
 listening for life out there</i>

00:04:09.515 --> 00:04:11.517
<i> for the last half century.</i>

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:14.654
<i>In 1960, astronomer Frank Drake
 began the search</i>

00:04:14.687 --> 00:04:17.390
<i> with a 85-foot radio
 telescope.</i>

00:04:17.423 --> 00:04:19.792
<i> He scanned for interstellar
 radio waves,</i>

00:04:19.825 --> 00:04:22.962
<i> but did not detect
 any recognizable signals.</i>

00:04:24.963 --> 00:04:29.402 line:0%
<i>Soon after, SETI, or Search for
 Extraterrestrial Intelligence,</i>

00:04:29.435 --> 00:04:31.404 line:0%
<i> was formed to continue
 our search</i>

00:04:31.437 --> 00:04:32.905
<i> for other life
 in the universe.</i>

00:04:33.405 --> 00:04:34.373
<i> [Mission Control]
 Liftoff.</i>

00:04:34.406 --> 00:04:35.474
<i> [Michael]
 Besides just listening,</i>

00:04:35.507 --> 00:04:37.677
<i> we've also launched
 physical messages</i>

00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:39.612
<i> like the Golden Records
 we put aboard</i>

00:04:39.645 --> 00:04:42.715
<i> both Voyager spacecraft
 in 1977.</i>

00:04:42.748 --> 00:04:45.785
<i> The records were recordings
of images and sounds from Earth</i>

00:04:45.818 --> 00:04:49.055
<i>that told a story of who we are
 as Earthlings,</i>

00:04:49.088 --> 00:04:52.391
<i> as well as coded instructions
 on how to play them back.</i>

00:04:52.424 --> 00:04:54.627
<i> Today, Doug and his team
 at METI</i>

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.398 line:0%
<i> are on a mission to send
 new messages to the stars.</i>

00:04:59.865 --> 00:05:03.035
Thank you for taking some time
to have a conversation with me.

00:05:03.068 --> 00:05:06.339
My first question
is simply this:

00:05:06.372 --> 00:05:08.407
where is everyone?

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:09.942
Are we alone?

00:05:09.975 --> 00:05:11.510
I don't think so.

00:05:11.543 --> 00:05:12.645
You know, we've been looking

00:05:12.678 --> 00:05:13.779
for over 60 years.

00:05:13.813 --> 00:05:16.482
And so that leads some people
to say we must be alone.

00:05:16.515 --> 00:05:17.850
The reality is, though,

00:05:17.883 --> 00:05:19.752
we have just
begun the search.

00:05:19.785 --> 00:05:23.689
I mean, we've looked at a few
tens of thousands of stars,

00:05:23.722 --> 00:05:28.027
and there are 400 billion stars
in our galaxy alone.

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:30.496
Billions of galaxies
in the universe.

00:05:30.529 --> 00:05:32.898
So I think we just need
to keep on looking.

00:05:32.931 --> 00:05:33.832
When you put it that way,

00:05:33.866 --> 00:05:35.100
it actually isn't
that surprising, is it?

00:05:35.133 --> 00:05:40.039
I mean, we are still discovering
species on our own planet today.

00:05:40.072 --> 00:05:42.708
At METI, we switch the process,

00:05:42.741 --> 00:05:44.910
and instead of just listening
for signals,

00:05:44.943 --> 00:05:48.447
we send powerful, intentional
signals to other stars

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:50.416
in the hope of getting
a reply.

00:05:50.449 --> 00:05:53.018
What do you say
to people who go, "Hold on,

00:05:53.051 --> 00:05:56.856
"we should not be alerting any
life out there to our presence.

00:05:56.889 --> 00:05:58.424
"It's just not worth the risk.

00:05:58.457 --> 00:06:00.126
In fact, it's irresponsible."

00:06:00.159 --> 00:06:02.895
I would say it is too late.

00:06:02.928 --> 00:06:04.597
The horse is out of the barn.

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:08.134
We have been announcing
our presence to the universe

00:06:08.167 --> 00:06:12.605
since the beginning of radio
and television.

00:06:12.638 --> 00:06:14.573
Any civilization
that has the ability

00:06:14.606 --> 00:06:16.442
to travel between the stars

00:06:16.475 --> 00:06:18.511
already picked up
<i> I Love Lucy.</i>

00:06:18.544 --> 00:06:21.113
So maybe the aliens
have been observing us,

00:06:21.146 --> 00:06:24.550
but they're waiting for us
to break the silence.

00:06:24.583 --> 00:06:26.585
So our goal isn't
to let them know

00:06:26.618 --> 00:06:27.987
we're here for the first time.

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:29.922
It's to really give
an indication

00:06:29.955 --> 00:06:31.690
that we want
to make contact.

00:06:31.723 --> 00:06:34.693
The one thing that's keeping me
from being really excited

00:06:34.726 --> 00:06:36.529
and comfortable
about sending a message out

00:06:36.562 --> 00:06:39.698
is that a lot of prominent
people have said, "Don't."

00:06:39.731 --> 00:06:41.967
There are some group
of scientists who have said

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.569
you shouldn't be doing this.

00:06:43.602 --> 00:06:44.637
Stephen Hawking.

00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:46.906
But that's an example
of someone very prominent

00:06:46.939 --> 00:06:49.608
who said you shouldn't transmit,

00:06:49.641 --> 00:06:51.911
because maybe the aliens
will come to Earth.

00:06:51.944 --> 00:06:53.712
To me it's notable that,
after his death,

00:06:53.745 --> 00:06:56.048
to commemorate his life,
his family,

00:06:56.081 --> 00:06:58.584
they transmitted his voice
out into space.

00:06:58.617 --> 00:07:02.488
Anyone and everyone can
transmit to extraterrestrials.

00:07:02.521 --> 00:07:04.790
So I think it's an incredible
contradiction

00:07:04.823 --> 00:07:07.560
for people involved in SETI
to say we shouldn't transmit,

00:07:07.593 --> 00:07:11.030
because the day they succeed,
everyone will be transmitting.

00:07:11.063 --> 00:07:16.202
Okay, so how do we craft
a message for E.T.?

00:07:16.235 --> 00:07:18.504
Well, it depends
what we would want to do.

00:07:18.537 --> 00:07:21.707
I would want to know something
about that civilization.

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:23.876
And so then we try
to figure out,

00:07:23.909 --> 00:07:26.679
what is it that we have
in common

00:07:26.712 --> 00:07:28.080
with the extraterrestrials?

00:07:28.113 --> 00:07:31.951
What do you think the aliens
would know that we know?

00:07:31.984 --> 00:07:33.486
I always go to math.

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:35.754
So that's the natural
starting place.

00:07:35.787 --> 00:07:39.091
But how can you communicate
the idea of numbers?

00:07:39.124 --> 00:07:40.693 align:start size:31% position:69%
Like this.

00:07:47.833 --> 00:07:49.835
[both clap]

00:07:49.868 --> 00:07:52.171
-Hey, look, we're communicating.
-Okay, okay, great, great.

00:07:52.204 --> 00:07:54.139
You could keep that up.
You could use that

00:07:54.172 --> 00:07:56.141
to count up to a million.

00:07:56.174 --> 00:07:59.245
But that doesn't capture
what it is to be human.

00:07:59.278 --> 00:08:00.313
Right.

00:08:00.346 --> 00:08:03.249
So you want to tell
a little bit about yourself.

00:08:03.282 --> 00:08:07.786
The goal, for me, is to learn
about other civilizations

00:08:07.819 --> 00:08:09.922 size:56% position:28%
if, in fact,
they're out there.

00:08:09.955 --> 00:08:11.790 size:63% position:31%
But I think
even if they're not,

00:08:11.823 --> 00:08:14.293
simply this process
of reflecting on what stories

00:08:14.326 --> 00:08:16.662
do we want to tell
about ourselves,

00:08:16.695 --> 00:08:19.598
how do we want to represent
ourselves to the universe,

00:08:19.631 --> 00:08:21.233
forces us to look
at ourselves anew.

00:08:21.266 --> 00:08:23.135
And I think that
can only be good.

00:08:29.675 --> 00:08:30.943
One of my favorite messages

00:08:30.976 --> 00:08:33.913
that humans have ever sent
for extraterrestrials

00:08:33.946 --> 00:08:37.216
to some day receive
was written in 1974

00:08:37.249 --> 00:08:39.752
by Frank Drake
and Carl Sagan.

00:08:39.785 --> 00:08:44.557 line:0%
They sent the message to a star
cluster 25,000 light years away.

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:50.062 line:0%
It contained 1,679
binary digits

00:08:50.095 --> 00:08:52.131
that, when decoded,

00:08:52.164 --> 00:08:53.899
created an image:

00:08:53.932 --> 00:08:57.136
the famous Arecibo message.

00:08:57.169 --> 00:09:00.739
This message is full of general
information about us.

00:09:00.772 --> 00:09:03.208
Up here in the white
are numbers.

00:09:03.241 --> 00:09:05.711
Now, since math is probably
pretty universal,

00:09:05.744 --> 00:09:07.079
I feel like it's fair to say

00:09:07.112 --> 00:09:09.214
that aliens will understand
that part.

00:09:09.247 --> 00:09:11.350
But what about some of these
other parts?

00:09:11.383 --> 00:09:14.019
This is a human figure,
but will aliens be able to tell

00:09:14.052 --> 00:09:15.187
that that is supposed to be

00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:17.723
the shape of the thing
that made this?

00:09:17.756 --> 00:09:21.193
Could an alien figure out
what all these symbols mean?

00:09:21.226 --> 00:09:24.229
For that matter, could a human
even correctly figure out

00:09:24.262 --> 00:09:25.664
what they all mean?

00:09:25.697 --> 00:09:27.733
And I bet that if you were
to ask two people

00:09:27.766 --> 00:09:30.002
to guess what all this means,

00:09:30.035 --> 00:09:32.204
you would get
two different answers.

00:09:32.237 --> 00:09:34.707
I want to give some humans
a message,

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:37.276
and I want to see how quickly
they come up with meanings

00:09:37.309 --> 00:09:40.245
I didn't put in there,
or conflicting interpretations,

00:09:40.278 --> 00:09:41.479
because if that happens,

00:09:41.513 --> 00:09:45.117
well it could spell trouble
for our ability to say much more

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:50.256
than simple mathematical truths
to whatever might be out there.

00:09:51.289 --> 00:09:53.192
<i> To help me answer
 this question,</i>

00:09:53.225 --> 00:09:55.394
<i> I recruited Dr. Steve Vance.</i>

00:09:55.427 --> 00:09:57.796
<i> Dr. Vance leads
 a habitability team</i>

00:09:57.829 --> 00:09:59.932
<i> for JPL's Astrobiology group,</i>

00:09:59.965 --> 00:10:02.968 line:0%
<i> meaning it's his job to think
 about the possibility</i>

00:10:03.001 --> 00:10:04.970 line:0%
<i> of life on other planets.</i>

00:10:05.003 --> 00:10:06.839
I don't think it's crazy

00:10:06.872 --> 00:10:10.376
that if the Arecibo message
is received,

00:10:10.409 --> 00:10:12.878
the alien civilization
that gets it

00:10:12.911 --> 00:10:15.814
will see all kinds
of meanings in it.

00:10:15.847 --> 00:10:17.116
They're going to see things
through the lens

00:10:17.149 --> 00:10:19.785
of how they experience
their world.

00:10:19.818 --> 00:10:22.021
And I think if we received
a message from outer space,

00:10:22.054 --> 00:10:23.922
we would think of the ones
we've sent out,

00:10:23.955 --> 00:10:25.424
and we would look
for these pieces in it.

00:10:25.457 --> 00:10:29.928
And maybe the message
contains none of those things.

00:10:29.961 --> 00:10:32.131
I'm really curious
about this hypothesis

00:10:32.164 --> 00:10:35.067
that they will find meaning
where there isn't any.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:36.802 size:63% position:31%
There's only
one way to find out.

00:10:36.835 --> 00:10:39.639
-Yeah. Let's do it.
-Let's do it.

00:10:43.909 --> 00:10:46.412
[Michael]<i> To find out how
 individuals' own backgrounds</i>

00:10:46.445 --> 00:10:49.348
<i> would influence their approach
 to a message from space,</i>

00:10:49.381 --> 00:10:51.717
<i> we sought out
 a veritable A-team</i>

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:53.886
<i> of critical thinkers
 and problem solvers</i>

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:55.054
<i> to put to the test.</i>

00:10:55.087 --> 00:10:57.723 line:0%
I'm a sophomore engineer,
and I have a PhD in physics.

00:10:57.756 --> 00:10:59.158 line:0%
I'm a game designer
and programmer.

00:10:59.191 --> 00:11:00.459 line:0%
I am a professional
poker player.

00:11:00.492 --> 00:11:02.428 line:0%
I'm a graphic artist
and app coder.

00:11:02.461 --> 00:11:05.731 line:0%
I teach college courses
in writing film and psychology.

00:11:05.764 --> 00:11:07.199
<i> This set of experts
 would be told</i>

00:11:07.232 --> 00:11:08.734
<i> that the message
 they were receiving</i>

00:11:08.767 --> 00:11:10.469
<i> was intercepted
 from outer space,</i>

00:11:10.502 --> 00:11:12.738
<i> and would be asked
 to decode it</i>

00:11:12.771 --> 00:11:14.473
<i> using a variety
 of office supplies</i>

00:11:14.506 --> 00:11:16.108
<i> and computer software.</i>

00:11:16.141 --> 00:11:17.843
<i> What they didn't know is that</i>

00:11:17.876 --> 00:11:20.479
<i> although similar to
 the original Arecibo message,</i>

00:11:20.512 --> 00:11:23.215
<i> our message is just noise.</i>

00:11:23.248 --> 00:11:25.117
<i> Would our group
 of experts notice</i>

00:11:25.150 --> 00:11:26.952
<i> that there was nothing
 to get,</i>

00:11:26.985 --> 00:11:30.923
<i> or apply their own meanings
to this indecipherable message?</i>

00:11:30.956 --> 00:11:32.892
<i> It was time to find out.</i>

00:11:34.493 --> 00:11:35.994
We received a message

00:11:36.027 --> 00:11:39.231
using a radio telescope
from outer space.

00:11:39.264 --> 00:11:42.267
Not the kind of thing
that naturally happens.

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:46.872
What we want to know
is what it says.

00:11:46.905 --> 00:11:50.943
A copy of the message
as received is on that laptop.

00:11:50.976 --> 00:11:54.146
This is an audio output
of that message.

00:11:54.179 --> 00:11:57.249
Using your individual expertise

00:11:57.282 --> 00:11:59.852
and the tools
that you have in front of you,

00:11:59.885 --> 00:12:03.422
please figure out
what this message is saying.

00:12:03.455 --> 00:12:05.157
This is not an easy task.

