There's going to be a repeating
pattern in there, probably.

00:12:50.435 --> 00:12:51.636
It seems like
there's only two notes.

00:12:51.670 --> 00:12:56.408
Yeah, it doesn't seem to go
any higher or lower than that.

00:12:56.441 --> 00:12:58.210 size:81% position:41%
So there's only two tones.
We're thinking some kind

00:12:58.243 --> 00:12:59.812 size:56% position:28%
of binary message,
zeros and ones,

00:12:59.845 --> 00:13:02.080 size:66% position:33%
We should probably
start transcribing it

00:13:02.113 --> 00:13:03.048
<i> and look for repeating
 patterns.</i>

00:13:03.081 --> 00:13:04.416 size:56% position:72%
Right off the bat,
all right?

00:13:04.449 --> 00:13:07.019
They're noticing two tones,
binary message.

00:13:07.052 --> 00:13:08.987
I think that's a very
human thing to do,

00:13:09.020 --> 00:13:11.290
because we already
come to this

00:13:11.323 --> 00:13:14.560
knowing that binary is this
great way to talk, right?

00:13:14.593 --> 00:13:18.530
So we're already seeing into it
what we expect to see.

00:13:18.563 --> 00:13:22.868
Okay, so, we have a way
to encode binary into letters.

00:13:22.901 --> 00:13:24.603
So if an alien intelligence
is sending things,

00:13:24.636 --> 00:13:25.804
we obviously wouldn't know that,

00:13:25.837 --> 00:13:28.106
-and it wouldn't be
the same language anyway.
-Right.

00:13:28.139 --> 00:13:30.275
So they're probably just sending
us straight numbers.

00:13:30.308 --> 00:13:33.212
Like, there's, you know,
universal language and all that.

00:13:33.245 --> 00:13:34.446
So we got to find out
what those numbers are.

00:13:34.479 --> 00:13:35.848
Okay, let's have
three people do this,

00:13:35.881 --> 00:13:37.583
just so we make sure
we don't miss anything.

