<i> the jumbled image
 will begin to emerge.</i>

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:19.217
<i> If the group can discover
 this feature of 1,679,</i>

00:15:19.250 --> 00:15:21.320
<i> they may be able to start
 breaking down the tones</i>

00:15:21.353 --> 00:15:23.522
<i> of the message
 into an image.</i>

00:15:23.555 --> 00:15:24.723 align:start size:28% position:72%
Ooh. Ooh!

00:15:24.756 --> 00:15:27.626
Hey, it's-- hey, yo,
this is important, guys.

00:15:27.659 --> 00:15:30.228
This number breaks down
to 23x73.

00:15:30.261 --> 00:15:31.330 align:start size:16% position:84%
Okay.

00:15:31.363 --> 00:15:33.465
Ah-ha. There it is.

00:15:33.498 --> 00:15:34.700
And that is
the only breakdown,

00:15:34.733 --> 00:15:37.002
because 23 and 73
are prime numbers.

00:15:37.035 --> 00:15:38.570
So that's its prime
factorization.

00:15:38.603 --> 00:15:41.473
So that is very relevant.

00:15:41.506 --> 00:15:45.143 size:81% position:59%
Wow. Look at the big brain
on that dude.

00:15:45.176 --> 00:15:46.277
[man]
<i> Do you think it's worth it</i>

00:15:46.311 --> 00:15:51.450
to try and straight up, like,
make a 23-by-73 grid,

00:15:51.483 --> 00:15:53.719
and then you could
say that the lows are white

00:15:53.752 --> 00:15:54.887
and the ones are black,

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:57.556
and maybe there's some kind
of image being sent there.

00:15:57.589 --> 00:15:58.724 align:start size:53% position:47%
I like that idea.

00:15:58.757 --> 00:15:59.792
Hey.

00:15:59.825 --> 00:16:01.093
[man]<i> I'm strongly
 with the graph idea.</i>

00:16:01.126 --> 00:16:03.996
[woman]
What I'm doing right now is I'm
pasting it into Excel,

00:16:04.029 --> 00:16:06.598
-and then we can graph it
in Excel and see.
-Yeah, that's good.

00:16:06.631 --> 00:16:07.732
[Bonnie]
You mean like fill the cells

00:16:07.766 --> 00:16:09.768
-Yeah.
-and make the numbers white,
and all that?

00:16:09.801 --> 00:16:11.036 align:start position:0%
Yeah.

00:16:11.069 --> 00:16:14.539
She's going to try to make this
a little easier by coloring

00:16:14.572 --> 00:16:16.308 size:75% position:63%
-all of the cells
that have a one in them.
-That's great.

00:16:16.341 --> 00:16:18.777
We picked these people because
of their knowledge

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:20.645
of mathematics
and physics and music.

00:16:20.678 --> 00:16:23.181
But their knowledge
of how to use Excel

00:16:23.214 --> 00:16:25.250
is proving to be the best skill.

00:16:25.283 --> 00:16:27.652
<i> Amazingly,
 in just a couple of hours,</i>

00:16:27.685 --> 00:16:29.488
<i> the team figured out
 how to break down</i>

00:16:29.521 --> 00:16:32.657
<i> our fake Arecibo message
 into an image.</i>

00:16:32.690 --> 00:16:35.227
<i> Will they try to find meaning
 in the message,</i>

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:37.662
<i> or will they realize
 it's just noise?</i>

00:16:37.695 --> 00:16:39.131
Oh, I'm done!
Guys, I'm done!

00:16:39.164 --> 00:16:40.265 align:end position:100%
-Oh, you did it.
-That was fast.

00:16:41.232 --> 00:16:43.602
[man]
That looks sadly random.

00:16:44.602 --> 00:16:48.373
That almost looks like it's
going to resolve into something.

00:16:48.406 --> 00:16:49.708
[woman]
Maybe it's a map.

00:16:50.809 --> 00:16:52.811
-Those aren't letters, are they?
-They could be.

00:16:52.844 --> 00:16:55.380
[man]
No, they're all back half
of the alphabet, then.

00:16:55.413 --> 00:16:56.782 size:69% position:66%
Except for
little nine over here.

00:16:56.815 --> 00:16:58.450
Little nine. Look at that little
nine.

00:16:58.483 --> 00:17:01.086
-[woman] Baby nine.
-[man] That's an "I", right?

00:17:01.119 --> 00:17:02.454
I'm pretty sure
there's nothing there.

00:17:02.487 --> 00:17:03.555
There's no pattern here.

00:17:03.588 --> 00:17:06.258
Do we agree, like, this probably
looks like nothing?

00:17:06.291 --> 00:17:09.461
[woman]
Yeah, I don't think going any
further with this is really...

00:17:09.494 --> 00:17:10.629
-Productive.
-Okay.

00:17:10.662 --> 00:17:12.364
<i> Our group had followed
 the clues correctly</i>

00:17:12.397 --> 00:17:13.532
<i> and built out an image,</i>

00:17:13.565 --> 00:17:16.268
<i> even though there wasn't one
 that made sense.</i>

00:17:16.301 --> 00:17:18.804
<i> And, incredibly, they didn't
 try to make sense of it.</i>

00:17:18.837 --> 00:17:19.972
<i> Within a matter of minutes,</i>

00:17:20.005 --> 00:17:22.340
<i> they realized it was random
 and moved on.</i>

00:17:22.373 --> 00:17:24.776
<i> So it was time to let them in
 on the ruse.</i>

00:17:24.809 --> 00:17:26.311 align:start position:0%
Hello, again.

00:17:26.344 --> 00:17:30.082
All right, so,
this is Steve Vance.

00:17:30.115 --> 00:17:32.217
He's taken the day off
from JPL.

00:17:32.250 --> 00:17:34.186 size:78% position:39%
Have you learned anything
about the message?

00:17:34.219 --> 00:17:35.320
What do you know?

00:17:35.353 --> 00:17:38.090
It seems very random still.

00:17:38.123 --> 00:17:39.658
Though it did have a nice prime
factorization.

00:17:39.691 --> 00:17:41.259
That did not seem
random to me.

00:17:41.292 --> 00:17:45.197
Let me show you guys
something new.

00:17:46.197 --> 00:17:47.499 size:44% position:78%
[man]
What the heck?

00:17:47.532 --> 00:17:49.134 align:start size:75% position:25%
It looks like 23 across.

00:17:49.167 --> 00:17:50.836
-I see how you're doing this.
-Oh, we were almost there!

00:17:50.869 --> 00:17:53.305
We tried arranging
these ones and zeros

00:17:53.338 --> 00:17:54.539
kind of in these blocks.

00:17:54.572 --> 00:17:56.274
[woman] But there's some
patterns repeating there

00:17:56.307 --> 00:17:59.211
that we don't actually have
mapped correctly here.

00:17:59.244 --> 00:18:02.614
[Michael]
Now, this is not the message
that you're looking at.

00:18:02.647 --> 00:18:05.084
This is the famous
Arecibo message.

00:18:05.884 --> 00:18:09.855
Now, what you have been
working on

00:18:09.888 --> 00:18:12.858
is this message,

00:18:12.891 --> 00:18:14.392
but randomized.

00:18:14.425 --> 00:18:15.694
[laughs]

00:18:15.727 --> 00:18:16.862 align:start size:41% position:59%
Thanks a lot.

00:18:16.895 --> 00:18:19.131
[all laugh]

00:18:19.164 --> 00:18:21.666
Oh, I'm just going to collapse
on the ground now.

00:18:21.699 --> 00:18:24.169
In a way, you guys were
quite successful.

00:18:24.202 --> 00:18:25.871
You, first of all,

00:18:25.904 --> 00:18:29.341
recognized the semi-prime nature
of this message very quickly,

00:18:29.374 --> 00:18:31.276
and tried to build an image.

00:18:31.309 --> 00:18:32.477
I was wondering
if you would start

00:18:32.510 --> 00:18:35.213
to see things there
that weren't.

00:18:35.246 --> 00:18:37.883
But it didn't really happen,
did it?

00:18:37.916 --> 00:18:40.252
I think the real reason
that we weren't interpreting

00:18:40.285 --> 00:18:41.286 align:start position:0%
anything out of that

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:43.488
is we were looking
for clearly defined patterns.

00:18:43.521 --> 00:18:45.490
We're looking
for something like this.

00:18:45.523 --> 00:18:47.325
This is actually
what we're looking for.

00:18:47.358 --> 00:18:48.927
Even symmetry would have been
a big thing for me.

00:18:48.960 --> 00:18:50.529 size:75% position:38%
If I'd seen any symmetry
in these patterns,

00:18:50.562 --> 00:18:52.430 size:66% position:33%
I would have said,
"This is not random."

00:18:52.463 --> 00:18:53.798 size:59% position:30%
I'm also interested
in knowing

00:18:53.831 --> 00:18:56.835 size:59% position:30%
the best kind
of message to send,

00:18:56.868 --> 00:18:59.604
because I have an opportunity
to send a message.

00:18:59.637 --> 00:19:01.706
You know, a marker
to where we are

00:19:01.739 --> 00:19:03.441 size:78% position:61%
is kind of
the biggest thing for me,

00:19:03.474 --> 00:19:05.944
but then it's like, do we really
want to tell them where we are?

00:19:05.977 --> 00:19:07.646
Is that something--
Do we want them to come visit?

00:19:07.679 --> 00:19:09.481
-I don't know.
-What do you guys think?

00:19:09.514 --> 00:19:13.185
Should we be sending messages
to outer space?

00:19:13.218 --> 00:19:14.352 size:31% position:84%
[all]
Yeah, yes.

00:19:14.385 --> 00:19:15.153 size:75% position:63%
[Matthew]
I don't think we should.

00:19:15.186 --> 00:19:17.222
Every single time
any civilization

00:19:17.255 --> 00:19:19.457
encounters any other
civilization,

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:21.960
and one is technologically
advanced, one guy gets crushed.

00:19:21.993 --> 00:19:24.930
You know, what if they're not
more advanced than us?

00:19:24.963 --> 00:19:25.998
What if we're at the same place,

00:19:26.031 --> 00:19:29.935
and the only way we can
communicate is like this?

00:19:29.968 --> 00:19:34.472
What if we can just exchange
the recipe for fusion?

00:19:34.505 --> 00:19:37.309
We would have so much to learn
from those people,

00:19:37.342 --> 00:19:41.279
and really nothing to lose
in that situation.

00:19:41.312 --> 00:19:42.180
You're making an argument

00:19:42.213 --> 00:19:43.381
that we almost have
a moral imperative

00:19:43.414 --> 00:19:46.218
to send our knowledge to share
with other civilizations.

00:19:46.251 --> 00:19:47.852
-Absolutely, yes.
-It's a really interesting
point.

00:19:47.885 --> 00:19:49.521
That's kind of where I land.

00:19:49.554 --> 00:19:50.889
Let's just think of this
as a way

00:19:50.922 --> 00:19:53.625
to preserve the stories
that we've been able to tell,

00:19:53.658 --> 00:19:56.328
which, by the way, we tell
better than the universe does.

00:19:56.361 --> 00:19:59.631
Thank you all so much.
This was a phenomenal exercise.

00:19:59.664 --> 00:20:01.767
[all]
Thanks. Thank you.

00:20:05.870 --> 00:20:08.506
You know, honestly, I thought
that the human tendency

00:20:08.539 --> 00:20:12.911
to find meaning where there is
none would more quickly emerge.

00:20:12.944 --> 00:20:14.713
But that didn't really happen.

00:20:14.746 --> 00:20:18.350
What I also didn't expect
was just how educational

00:20:18.383 --> 00:20:19.985
the whole challenge
would be.

00:20:20.018 --> 00:20:23.588
I mean, I saw some human flaws
and biases at work,

00:20:23.621 --> 00:20:27.626
but more generally,
I saw the human mind at work,

00:20:27.659 --> 00:20:29.427
who we are.

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:30.495
Which kind of makes sense,
right?

00:20:30.528 --> 00:20:32.897
I mean, the Voyager
Golden Record

00:20:32.930 --> 00:20:36.368
really isn't just a neat thing
for extraterrestrials.

00:20:36.401 --> 00:20:42.007 line:0%
It's a neat archive by,
of and for us.

00:20:45.076 --> 00:20:47.479
I don't think we will all
ever agree

00:20:47.512 --> 00:20:49.547
about whether or not
we should be sending messages

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:52.784
to outer space
announcing that we are here.

00:20:52.817 --> 00:20:53.651
But here's the thing.

00:20:53.685 --> 00:20:56.554
Sending focused messages
to outer space

00:20:56.587 --> 00:20:59.557
requires technology
that not all of us have.

00:20:59.590 --> 00:21:01.660
So only those with access

00:21:01.693 --> 00:21:04.362
can say hello to
extraterrestrials if they want.

00:21:04.395 --> 00:21:07.465
But who chose them
to speak for us,

00:21:07.498 --> 00:21:09.734
for all of Earth?

00:21:09.767 --> 00:21:11.936
Well, I've come here,
to Vazquez Rocks State Park,

00:21:11.969 --> 00:21:14.572
to talk to a man
who is changing that.

00:21:14.605 --> 00:21:18.043
He is democratizing active SETI,
because the service he has built

00:21:18.076 --> 00:21:21.346
is allowing anyone to send
any message they want

00:21:21.379 --> 00:21:23.014
to outer space.

00:21:23.047 --> 00:21:25.717 line:0%
<i> He's an expert in the field
 of alien communication</i>

00:21:25.750 --> 00:21:27.852 line:0%
<i> with a doctorate in elementary
 particle physics,</i>

00:21:27.885 --> 00:21:31.990
<i> and he's the one who's going
 to help me send my message.</i>

00:21:32.023 --> 00:21:35.694
Tell me about the way
you are talking to aliens

00:21:35.727 --> 00:21:37.729
and helping other
people do it.

00:21:37.762 --> 00:21:41.099
Well, I have built a website,
called SpaceSpeak.com.

00:21:41.132 --> 00:21:44.469
And it allows people
to send a text in audio

00:21:44.502 --> 00:21:47.605
or a image message
out into space.

00:21:47.638 --> 00:21:52.077
My view is, as many people
that can reach out to aliens

00:21:52.110 --> 00:21:54.946
or the universe in general,
the better.

00:21:54.979 --> 00:21:57.749
What are you using
to transmit these messages?

00:21:57.782 --> 00:22:00.819 size:88% position:56%
Radio waves. Radio waves are
just another form of photon.

00:22:00.852 --> 00:22:04.889
And once a photon is broadcast
into space, it persists.

00:22:04.922 --> 00:22:07.125
It never dies.
It never decays.

00:22:07.158 --> 00:22:09.761
A million years from now,
maybe the earth is gone,

00:22:09.794 --> 00:22:11.963
maybe the solar system is gone,

00:22:11.996 --> 00:22:14.566 size:59% position:70%
but your message
is still out there,

00:22:14.599 --> 00:22:17.535 align:start size:69% position:31%
and essentially become
archaeological photons

00:22:17.568 --> 00:22:21.906 align:start size:81% position:19%
for some future generation
to see what we were about.

00:22:21.939 --> 00:22:24.042
-I want to do this.
-Absolutely, let's do it.

00:22:24.075 --> 00:22:25.510
-Awesome.
-Great.

00:22:27.478 --> 00:22:28.913
Going to take a chair
right here.

00:22:28.946 --> 00:22:31.049
-And...
-This is it.

00:22:31.082 --> 00:22:32.984 size:72% position:36%
This is the Space Speak
transmitter.

00:22:33.017 --> 00:22:34.986
This is a transmitter box here.

00:22:35.019 --> 00:22:37.823 size:59% position:30%
And the antenna
is right back here.

00:22:38.423 --> 00:22:39.991
I've been thinking
about this a lot,

00:22:40.024 --> 00:22:41.559
and I've spoken
to a lot of people

00:22:41.592 --> 00:22:46.798 size:78% position:61%
about what to send,
how to write the message,

00:22:46.831 --> 00:22:48.666
and whether or not
I should send anything at all.

00:22:48.699 --> 00:22:51.069
I don't think this is something
to take as fact.

00:22:51.102 --> 00:22:53.405
It's my personal opinion.

00:22:53.438 --> 00:22:56.708
I don't have any fear
that this is dangerous.

00:22:56.741 --> 00:22:58.877
-Yeah.
-I spent a lot of time

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:00.145
constructing what I believe

00:23:00.178 --> 00:23:03.681
to be a really neat,
clever idea.

00:23:03.714 --> 00:23:05.884
I was going to not send
a two-dimensional image

00:23:05.917 --> 00:23:06.918 align:start size:53% position:47%
like the Arecibo,

00:23:06.952 --> 00:23:09.187
but a three-dimensional image
made of voxels.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:10.822
And I got really into this.

00:23:10.855 --> 00:23:14.993
And then after talking to you
and really thinking about

00:23:15.026 --> 00:23:19.998 size:81% position:59%
the point of communicating
with outer space,

00:23:20.031 --> 00:23:21.866 align:start size:41% position:59%
beyond Earth,

00:23:21.899 --> 00:23:24.569 align:start size:50% position:50%
I...I just think

00:23:24.602 --> 00:23:28.473
to decide what to say
and how to say it.

00:23:28.506 --> 00:23:32.143
is an exercise in learning
how we communicate at all.

00:23:32.176 --> 00:23:34.145
-Yes.
-It's always coming back

00:23:34.178 --> 00:23:35.514
to who we are.

00:23:36.581 --> 00:23:38.917 size:81% position:59%
My grandmother passed away
a few days ago.

00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:40.585 align:start position:0%
I'm so sorry
to hear that.

00:23:40.618 --> 00:23:43.221
I'm actually leaving tomorrow
to her funeral,

00:23:43.254 --> 00:23:46.057
and I'll get to see
all of my family.

00:23:46.090 --> 00:23:49.127
And obviously I'm never going
to forget my grandma.

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:52.630
And the way she, you know,
made me who I am,

00:23:52.663 --> 00:23:56.067
that will, in a way, like echo
like ripples in a pond, right?

00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:57.802
For generations to come.

00:23:57.835 --> 00:24:02.207
But this is a message
made of light

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:07.012
that will be around forever...

00:24:07.778 --> 00:24:10.215
until the universe ends,
somehow.

00:24:10.248 --> 00:24:12.183
So I have the last photograph

00:24:12.216 --> 00:24:14.219
that was ever taken
of us together.

00:24:14.252 --> 00:24:16.955
I'd like to send
that picture out.

00:24:16.988 --> 00:24:19.124
-Let's do it.
-Okay.

00:24:22.727 --> 00:24:24.796
This photo is her
in the hospital,

00:24:24.829 --> 00:24:27.866
using one of those, like,
grabber tools, you know,

00:24:27.899 --> 00:24:30.235
to pull my beard hairs
and hurt me.

00:24:30.268 --> 00:24:31.169
[laughs]

00:24:31.203 --> 00:24:34.138
And she was so weak,
but with that tool,

00:24:34.171 --> 00:24:35.540
she could pinch.

00:24:35.573 --> 00:24:36.908
-Oh, that's awesome.
-It's a great picture

00:24:36.941 --> 00:24:38.477
of who we were.

00:24:39.277 --> 00:24:42.280
She wasn't a big fan of aliens

00:24:42.313 --> 00:24:43.781
as far as I know,

00:24:43.814 --> 00:24:46.618
but it's us
caught in this moment

00:24:46.651 --> 00:24:48.586
that I think I want
to remember,

00:24:48.619 --> 00:24:50.288
and I want the universe
to remember.

00:24:50.321 --> 00:24:53.024
So...

00:24:53.057 --> 00:24:53.691 align:start size:56% position:44%
well, let's do it.

00:24:53.725 --> 00:24:56.228
Yeah. Go ahead and hit "send."

00:24:57.295 --> 00:24:59.797 size:53% position:73%
Wow. It's sent.
And look at that.

00:24:59.830 --> 00:25:04.802 size:84% position:58%
-It's already 229,435 miles
away from Earth.
-Yes.

00:25:04.835 --> 00:25:07.205
I don't think she ever traveled
that far in her entire life.

00:25:07.238 --> 00:25:09.140
-Now she has.
-She has now, absolutely.

00:25:09.173 --> 00:25:11.943
[Michael]
And she will continue traveling.

00:25:11.976 --> 00:25:15.213
Your grandmother
will touch the universe. Yeah.

00:25:15.246 --> 00:25:16.648
Peter, thank you
very much.

00:25:16.681 --> 00:25:19.684 size:81% position:41%
You are very welcome, sir.
It was a pleasure.

